<script type="text/javascript" language="javascript" src="https://live.primis.tech/live/liveView.php?s=120997&schain=1.0,1!publift.com,01K5AHM87E14YH1C83WXZ8HCHJ,1&cbuster=%%CACHEBUSTER%%"></script>
<!-- End of code from Primis --></div>
<p>â€œMama Prefect, God bless you. Youâ€™re in a go-slow, oh! I beg your pardon. Iâ€™ll clear the road for you, now now.â€</p>
<p>The prefectural badge on the windshield hadnâ€™t escaped his attention. I got back into the car and rolled down the window.</p>
<p>I usually refused to take advantage of the priority lane. Today, I needed to keep my arms and legs busy. Avoid potholes, taxis, and motorcycles slamming on their brakes without warning, pedestrians who cross without looking. To get the letter from the FÃ¨nn Town Hall out of my head, I had to keep my attention focused elsewhere.</p>
<p>â€œAbeg, Mama Prefect, save a brother.â€ â€œAnd who will save <em>me</em>?â€ I joked.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_1 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_1"></div></div>
<p>â€œMama, Mama, times are tough . . . Your sister at home dey always on my back.â€</p>
<p>I took my purse from the passenger seat, pulled out a ï¬ve-thousand franc bill, rolled it up in my ï¬st, then palmed it to the officer. In no time, he had cleared a path. I jammed the key into the ignition.</p>
<p>The SUV bounced down the dirt alleyway that led to the studio. It was a far cry from the paved roads and air-conditioned streets of the Fleuve neighborhood where I lived with Tashun. This district, where the government once housed Ministry of Education employees, had grown dilapidated since it was sold off to private investors, but the rent was affordable. Impoverished, like most parts of the capital, the CitÃ© des Enseignants wouldnâ€™t be able to avoid the status of â€œghettoâ€ much longer, despite the flowering flame trees that brightened the houses. Everywhere, families had moved into makeshift shelters cobbled together from sheet metal and wood. During the rainy season, their hovels turned into hovels on stilts. An expensive renovation to raise its foundation protected Samyâ€™s studio from the elements; high above it all, the veranda provided a stunning, unobstructed view of poverty and all its ills. Samy knew that I used to live nearby. I would have preferred he settle somewhere else, but he said the atmosphere stimulated his creativity. And he really did seem more proliï¬c since heâ€™d been working there. If the exhibitionâ€”his ï¬rst solo showâ€”was a success, he would ï¬nally be able to turn the page on the moldings he sold to tourists on the hunt for cheap souvenirs. I was eager to see his sculptures, his new work. I knew this wasnâ€™t the right time to mention the letter I had received. I also knew that I would mention it anyway. Who else could I talk to about it? Under different circumstances, regarding any other subject, I would have laughed as I showed him the obsequious, handwritten note the mayor of FÃ¨nn had added to the bottom of the page. <em>The prospect of serving His Excellency and Madam Excellency fills me with deferential joy. </em>My laugh, which Tashun always found inappropriate, would have slipped past my lips. But not this time. This letter didnâ€™t make me want to laugh at all.</p>
<p>â€œThe activist artist in all his glory!â€ Samy exclaimed, pointing at four sculptures supported by wooden rods. Hollow cheeks, red eyes, dark circles. He clearly wasnâ€™t getting enough sleep. â€œThis isnâ€™t the ï¬nal scale, just maquettes,â€ he continued. â€œIt will be bigger, the height of a grown man. Iâ€™m doing ten on the same theme.â€</p>
<p>Four male ï¬gures stood before me, their long necks headless, two-thirds of their abdomens replaced by their heads lodged between their solar plexuses and belly buttons. The square heads overflowed on all sides to create love handles and sagging bellies. Bloody nostrils, mouths twisted in pain, eyes wide with the same despair found in Courbetâ€™s <em>The Desperate Man. </em>The faces of the four terracotta characters Samy had sculpted were vaguely familiar. I thought for a moment. The president and the three vice presidents.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_2 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_2"></div></div>
<p>â€œSo?â€ he asked anxiously.</p>
<p>â€œYou really want to put this on display?â€</p>
<p>â€œThereâ€™s more, not just sculptures,â€ he said as he gestured toward the far end of the warehouse. â€œIâ€™m still thinking about the title for the show, but I think Iâ€™ve got something. Come with me.â€</p>
<p>A rattan bookcase, volumes on sculpture and photography, old newspapers, a pile of drawing notebooks, and on top of them, a sheet of paper.</p>
<p>â€œCome sit here, youâ€™ll be more comfortable while you read,â€ he urged as he pushed toward me the tall bamboo stool where he usually sat to draw and held out the piece of paper.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_3 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_3"></div></div>
<p><em>Ante Mortem. </em>Before death. As I read, I grew uneasy. In Zambuena, people werenâ€™t arrested for expressing disagreement with the president or his party anymore. Samy had the right to sculpt and write what he wanted, to criticize whomever he chose. That was his role. The important thing was that he have no political ambitions, and since he didnâ€™t, there was nothing to fear. I only hoped that he wasnâ€™t lying to himself so deftly that he actually believed that choosing the right type of clayâ€”sandstone, ceramic, porcelain, or kaolinâ€”and obediently following the meticulous, thankless steps required to create a sculpture or a bas-relief would be enough to influence the status quo. He couldnâ€™t actually believe that a bold and powerful piece of art forged from nothing could force society to deviate from its ï¬xed trajectory. An activist artist, fantastic! Tashun would be sure to choke on that. â€œYour friend is a constant thorn in my side!â€ I could already hear him bray.</p>
<p>A projector displayed an experimental ï¬lm on the floor: overweight children devouring banknotes, laughing hysterically with each mouthful, while others looked on angrily, licking their lips. I made a mental note to ask Samy if the bills were real or from Zambony, our local version of Monopolyâ€”in the video, they looked authentic. Against the wall, a plywood trestle bore a series of 24 x 32-inch black-and-white photographs. Bodies of children, teens, the elderly, men, and women. Bodies pieced together to create a two-headed, multi-sexed fresco. Was it in keeping with the times? Was it good? Beautiful? Modern? I didnâ€™t know what to think except that I was troubled by the combination of buttocks as old as Methuselah with a young manâ€™s head, a grandmotherâ€™s withered breasts, childrenâ€™s legs, and sex organs of different sizes and types. Not to mention the obese little gluttons.</p>
<p>Last but not least, a series of photographs titled <em>The Aquatics </em>featured terriï¬ed faces emerging from wastewater and flooding, ID cards floating, women hoisting babies, lamps, or suitcases overhead, the swollen face of a drowned man. The images werenâ€™t new. Every year during the rainy season, the same ones, more or less, appeared on television screens and newspaper pages. But Samyâ€™s frameâ€”rusted corrugated sheet metal, scrap metal, and papier mÃ¢chÃ©â€”and his juxtaposition of these cataclysmic images with pictures of carefree couples lying in a ï¬eld of ripening corn with their children, ampliï¬ed the radical despair that was bursting from every scene. My eyes were full. When had Samy had time to do all this? His anxiety was stifling.</p>
<p>â€œSo?â€</p>
<p>I didnâ€™t know where to start.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><!-- GAM 22020028882/LTHB_lithubcom/Article_Incontent_4 -->
<div data-fuse="Article_Incontent_4"></div></div>
<p>â€œIf you donâ€™t like it, you can say so, KatmÃ©!â€ he exclaimed with a reproachful look.</p>
<p>â€œCome on, donâ€™t get upset. Itâ€™s just that . . . How can I put this . . . ? Itâ€™s . . .â€ I despised my voice for jumping an octave without my consent. I asked to see it all again, once, twice, three times. How I wish I had been able to declare with certainty, â€œI like this but not that.â€ Samy believed that a lack of linguistic precision resulted from a lack of sincerity; he would ask me to ï¬nd the words. What little I know about sculpture and the visual arts I owe to him. The library catalogue at the high school where we met was not so bold as to include the ï¬ne arts; and growing up with Mama RÃ©ciaâ€”whose ï¬erce devotion to the Bible and the Eucharist limited all attempts to embrace other forms of creationâ€”certainly never exposed me to Sow, Depara, or El Anatsui. Samy slid down the wall to sit on the floor and extended his legs.</p>
<p>A part of the image from the video projector reflected off his plastic mules. I sat down in his rocking chair, the sole comfortable seat in the room. Samy only sat in it when he wanted to â€œunlockâ€ his creativity. I looked down at him and steeled myself to say whatever I thought as it came to me, no hesitation or overthinking. â€œMaybe thereâ€™s too much to take in at once. Itâ€™s very dense, Samy.â€</p>
<p>â€œItâ€™s my ï¬rst solo show! It canâ€™t be ordinary!â€ Anger loomed in his voice. He made as though to stand, but stayed seated, gathering his knees beneath his chin for a moment before stretching them back out.</p>
<p>â€œSculpture is your art, not the rest of this stuff!â€</p>
<p>â€œItâ€™s all my art! Some of these photos are four years old. I recorded the video footage two years ago during a workshop with my students. Iâ€™m obese like the kids in the video, obese and overfull of everything I want to show people. Did you really think I had done all this in two months?â€</p>
<p>â€œYou should narrow your focus a bit, Samy. Youâ€™ll suffocate people, otherwise. You should tone it down a little. Really, itâ€™s too much.â€</p>
<p>He stood up, sullen, and leaned back against the wall. The fat children burst into laughter on the hem of his pants. I left the rocking chair to stand across from the photos of the flooding again.</p>
<p>â€œYou really donâ€™t like it, do you?â€ he asked, coming closer. I frowned. â€œTheir faces . . . Itâ€™s too raw, Samy.â€</p>
<p>â€œWhat these people live through is raw! Not everyone is lucky enough to live in the Fleuve neighborhood. Youâ€™re starting to worry me! Keuna says theyâ€™re very good. The photos and everything else!â€</p>
<p>â€œKeuna thinks itâ€™s very good, well thatâ€™s great, Iâ€™m thrilled for you. When did I lose the right to say that itâ€™s not perfect?â€ I asked, my tone drier than I would have liked. Hearing him mention Keuna always annoyed me. â€œYour sculptures, your titleâ€”<em>Ante Mortem</em>â€”youâ€™re looking for trouble! Itâ€™s like giving unripe plantain to a newborn. Your Keuna, who loves to go around playing White Lady all the time, how long has she even lived here? When Tashun sees this! Letâ€™s not forget that heâ€™s bankrolling it all!â€ As soon as the ï¬nal words crossed my lips, I could taste ash in my mouth. You canâ€™t choke ash back down.</p>
<p>Samy let out a nervous laugh. â€œWhat was that? What did you say, KatmÃ©?â€ His lips curled into a bitter line. I reached my hand out to him, full of regret. He recoiled. â€œKeuna says it will be a success. Iâ€™ll pay you back. I swear Iâ€™ll pay you back.â€</p>
<p>â€œSamy, that was stupid. Iâ€™m sorry.â€</p>
<p>His features hardened and he grasped his arms across his chest, his back to the wall once more. I tried to unclasp his arms, but he pushed me away. How could I have said such a thing? My tongue could be sharp and merciless, but never with Samy. It was the letter. The letter at the bottom of my purse. The letter and Tashunâ€™s extravagant plans. I needed to hurt someone. Samy was my unlucky victim. â€œThat was hateful,â€ I said, pleading now. â€œTashun doesnâ€™t even know about the money or the studio. Please . . . Iâ€™m sorry . . . What do I know? I go on and on, but I donâ€™t even know how to hold a drawing pencil properly! Samy . . .â€</p>
<p>He turned his red eyes toward me. He was a nervous wreck. He was a nervous wreck and, though he called me his airport, the safest place for him to land, his better half, I hadnâ€™t noticed. As usual. He pushed off the wall and made his way to the far end of the studio, pulling aside the curtain that hid the small private space that he had set up for himself, and lay down on his wrought-iron bed.</p>
